# Shared E/W KVCache Design

#### Danny Harnik, Maroon Ayoub, Or Ozery, Liran Shour, Michal Malka, Vita Bortnikov, Nili Guy

## Summary

This is a design for the well lit shared E/W KV caching. It encompasses all related KVCache functions that are cross vLLM engines, including **KVCache-aware routing** and **KV Cache sharing**. This should complement and build on capabilities of N/S KVCache offloading which includes offloading and reloading KV tensor from a single vLLM engine onto CPU RAM and local storage (without sharing across vLLM engines).

## Motivation 
Create a simple native llm-d kv sharing and kv-aware routing infrastructure.  
### Goals 
* Implement a **simple** modular llm-d native E/W KV sharing mechnism. 
* Integrate with native N/S KV offloading
* Support both sharing and KV-aware routing
* flexible to share between all layers (GPU,CPU, local storage and shared storage)  

## Design
At a high level the desired goal is to maintain **a cluster-wide view of all available KV cache tensors** and where they currently reside. This includes **GPU memory, CPU memory** and various **storage** options (local storage or shared storage). Once a full view exists, optimal decisions can be made as to how to obtain KV tensors for computations. This starts with routing the request to the longest available prefix, preferably in GPU. And continues with moving and sharing KV tensors. Preferably using the simplest and fastest available connection to retrieve needed KV tensors.   
Once a vLLM engine identifies that it is missing prefilled KV values, it will first look for these in the N/S path, and if still missing will further explore the E/W path. Using the full cluster view, a matching prefix can be identified and pulled onto the corresponding GPU.

While finding the best available KV match clusterwide is the eventual goal of this design, simplicity is also a key goal and we want to use a staged approach that adds capabilities in phases, perhaps leaving some options out if they do not prove worthwhile.

## Key Components

We envision the following Key components: 

1. **Transport framework** (likely NIXL based) \- once it is decided that KV tensors have to be sent between two locations, this framework should choose the best possible communication route including available optimizations for storage or for GPU2GPU communications (and perform the actual communication)  
2. **KV Cache cluster-wide index** \- this is the key component for cluster wide visibility. It should contain a mapping between Block-IDs (hash based) to the locations in which they exist. The mapping could be **1-to-many** if multiple occurrences of the same tensors exist.   
3. **KV event brokers** \-  similar to connectors, these enable vLLM to notify llm-d about the content of KV tensors inside vLLM engines. A version of this was implemented by Nvidia folks in vLLM and merged recently ([https://github.com/vllm-project/vllm/pull/16750](https://github.com/vllm-project/vllm/pull/16750)). This component should be expanded to span the KV events contents of CPU RAM and local storage. Namely integrate the event broker with the N/S solution.   
4. **KV Event handler \-**  This component receives the events generated by the event broker and updates the index accordingly.     
5. **KV E/W connector \-** this connector is retrieval centric. It queries the index to find suitable KV of a matching prefix and invokes the transport mechanism to pull these values.    
6. **KVCache-aware Router** \- uses the index for routing decisions (similar to the current inference-scheduler implementation) 


## Roadmap

Phase 1: 

* Choose or build a suitable N/S component as a starting point  
* Create basic KV event broker for N/S component  
* KV event handler  
* Index \- can start with Redis and then explore other options  
* EW connector  
  * Use NIXL as underlying transport for all possible inter process communications  
* Shared storage integration (simple, no evictions) 

Phase 2: 

* Shared storage management (including evictions)  
* Proactive placement/migration throughout the cluster  
  * Implemented iteratively, starting with router-level migration through request duplication, then moved to a lower level using the NIXL control-plane directly  
  * Proactive cache placement, migration and duplications is estimated to prove useful in high-load scenarios that involve N/S KV-cache squeeze. It could also be useful to pre-deploy KV-caches in identifiable Agentic applications.  
    * At this time Mooncake is the only supporter of this functionality

    

## Further points and questions

* Storage can consist of either **local storage** (in which case holding a location in the index is crucial) or **shared storage** (in this case location is less critical).   
* The **shared storage** option can and should be index-less, letting the storage directory structure serve as an index for the storage. In such a case the storage is consulted only if a value is not found in the main index.   
  * There could be use of auxiliary data structure to help with lookups in the storage (e.g. a Bloom filter).   
* The design here must be tightly integrated with the N/S design, but can be modular to use several N/S offloading mechanisms. The interface points with the N/S approach are in the event broker and in adding an agent for the transport layer, enabling communication between processes belonging to separate vLLM engines.  
* Sharing using storage could potentially be done also using the N/S mechanism. This should be considered in its design.    
* The index may also be used to hold element temperature in order to facilitate better location management decisions.  
* Should understand how PD disaggregation can be run using this framework   
* Do we share a disk offloading independently between vLLM nodes (this can be not efficient)?
